(221, 1, '2012-11-28 23:28:31', '2012-11-28 12:28:31', 'Hard work, passion and an evergrowing palate are the basis on which Justin has built an enviable culinary reputation – ensuring that he is a chef in demand.\r\nJustin’s love affair with quality food started at the age of three when his parents travelled extensively throughout the UK and Europe for work, tasting food along the way that Australia had not yet even seen, let alone embraced. Then in his early teenage years there were trips to South East Asia. What the family was eating at the dinner table was changed dramatically.\r\n\r\nJustin’s palate was not that of the usual school kid. He had already grasped sophisticated flavour combinations and felt the comfort of being involved in the preparation, or even cooking, of the evening meal. Having the advantage of being in close proximity to the Adelaide markets and the local Chinatown, hosting dinner party for friends at the weekend was a regular occurrence. This was a rewarding time spent on seasonal menu preparation and experimentation in building a repertoire of dishes.\r\nLike many a great chef, one of Justin’s first jobs was at McDonalds, and he gives his first manager the kudos for instilling his staff with discipline and the ability to work under strict time guidelines – qualities which would stand him in good stead in the future. Justin started his serious work as a kitchen hand at a new boutique hotel in Adelaide, The Bijou, where the head chef was a protégé of the renowned Cheong Liew, of the iconic Neddys restaurant.\r\nHaving the advantage of being in close proximity to the Adelaide markets and the local Chinatown, hosting dinner party for friends at the weekend was a regular occurrence. This was a rewarding time spent on seasonal menu preparation and experimentation in building a repertoire of dishes.\r\nLike many a great chef, one of Justin’s first jobs was at McDonalds, and he gives his first manager the kudos for instilling his staff with discipline and the ability to work under strict time guidelines – qualities which would stand him in good stead in the future. Justin started his serious work as a kitchen hand at a new boutique hotel in Adelaide, The Bijou, where the head chef was a protégé of the renowned Cheong Liew, of the iconic Neddys restaurant.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Profile', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '12-revision-6', '', '', '2012-11-28 23:28:31', '2012-11-28 12:28:31', '', 12, 'http://chefjustinbentley.com/12-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
